User 
@{"Edit...            " link MnEditUM} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}U 


@endnode 


@node mnnew "Project/New" 

@{b}@{u}Project/New@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{I}A @{UB}@{UI} N

Creates a new project with a mask window. It contains no records or 
fields. You may create a new database or @{"Open" link MnOpen} a saved database. 

See also: @{"Open" link MnOpen} 
@endnode 
@node mnerase "Project/Erase" 

@{b}@{u}Project/Erase@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} Z

Erases all data in the current project, the project will be in a status 
like immediately after calling @{"Project/New" link MnNew}. If data have changed since 
last saving, you will be asked before the data will be erased. 

@endnode 
@node mnopen "Project/Open..." 

@{b}@{u}Project/Open...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} O

Opens a ASL requester and loads the selected Fiasco project into the 
current project window. If there are any unsaved data, you will be asked, 
whether you want to save them first. 

    If Amiga OS 3.0 is available, Fiasco will increase the buffer-size of 
the file. This speeds up the load process considerabily. 
@endnode 
@node mnoptions "Project/Options..." 

@{b}@{u}Project/Options...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} $

This menuitem opens the @{"options requester" link RqOptions}, which can be used for editing 
projectspecific options. That are: 

@{b}·@{ub}  @{"Mask stretching" Link stretch} 

@{b}·@{ub}  Name of author and annotations 

@{b}·@{ub}  filename of project 
The last point makes it possible to change to name of the project 
without the need to call @{"Save as" link MnSaveAs}. 
@endnode 
@node mnstatistic "Project/Statistic..." 

@{b}@{u}Project/Statistic...@{ub}@{uu}

no Shortcut

Shows a few informations for the current project. Example:
One Record requires about 100 Byte RAM. 200 Records of this project need 
about 19 KByte RAM. There is space for about 2300 more Records. 

    The memory required for the project and the basic fields is not 
included.  
@endnode 
@node mnreloadrels "Project/Reload Rels" 

@{b}@{u}Project/Reload Rels@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui} !

This item reloads all relations in the current project, like it happened 
while loading the project. This is particularly useful, if you have 
deactivated @{"Settings/Update Relations?" Link MnUpdateRelations} and changed some keys and want to 
see the result.  
@endnode 


@node mnsave "Project/Save" 

@{b}@{u}Project/Save@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} S

Save writes the data of the current project under the same name to disk. 
If you want to save the project under a different name, you have to use 
@{"Save as" Link MnSaveAs} or @{"Options" Link MnOptions} to change the name and then Save. 

    If Amiga OS 3.0 is available, Fiasco will increase the buffer-size of 
the file. This speeds up the save process considerably. 
@endnode 


@node mnsaveas "Project/Save As..." 

@{b}@{u}Project/Save As...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} A

Here you may save the current project under a new name. The name will be 
requested using an ASL requester and will be kept after saving. 

    If Amiga OS 3.0 is available, Fiasco will increase the buffer-size of 
the file. This speeds up the save process considerably. 
@endnode 


@node mnimport "Project/Import..." 

@{b}@{u}Project/Import...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} I

Opens the @{"import requester" Link RqImport}, the GUI interface for the import function of 
Fiasco. You can use import to load data from foreign databases into 
Fiasco. 

@endnode 


@node mnexport "Project/Export..." 

@{b}@{u}Project/Export...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} E

Opens the @{"export requester" Link RqExport}, the GUI interface for the export function of 
Fiasco. You can use export to save data in a format, which can be read by 
other databases. 
@endnode 


@node mnabout "Project/About..." 

@{b}@{u}Project/About...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} ?

This item shows a small requester, which gives informations about 
version, copyright and some system internal data. 

@endnode 


@node mnquit "Project/Quit" 

@{b}@{u}Project/Quit@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} Q

This item closes the current project. If it has been changed and has not 
been saved yet, you will be asked, whether you want to do this. If this 
project is the last one, which Fiasco has currently open, Fiasco will 
exit. 

@endnode 


@node mnaddrecord "Record/Add Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Add Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} +

Adds a new record to the record list of the current project. Each Field 
contains then it's init cont, which is normally nothing. If the list is 
open, a new line will be inserted. 

    If a @{"Filter" link Filter} is active, the new record will be automatically declared 
valid. If you want that new Records are filtered correctly, you will have 
to select @{"Compare/Edit Filter" link MnEditFilter} again and simply click on Ok. 

    This menuitem may only be selected in the @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Record/Remove Record" link MnRemoveRecord} 

@endnode 
@node mnduplicaterecord "Record/Duplicate Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Duplicate Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui} 2

Creates an exact copy of the current record. All init cont attributes 
will be ignored. Even a field with gimme unique Key will contain the old 
value. That means, that two records with the same "unique" Key will 
exist. 

@endnode 
@node mnremoverecord "Record/Delete Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Delete Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} -

Removes the current record and the data in it. If the are relations, 
which search for a key, which was defined in this record, they will find 
in the future nothing. 

    This menuitem may be selected only in the @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. If you have 
selected @{"Setting/Security-Requester?" link MnSecurityRequester}, you will be asked before 
proceeding. 

See also: @{"Record/Add Record" link MnAddRecord}, @{"Record/Delete all Records" link mndeleteallrecords} 
@endnode 
@node mndeleteallrecords "Record/Delete all Records" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Delete all Records@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} @

Removes all records in the current project. The mask will not be deleted 
by this function. 

    Record/Delete all Records may be only called in record mode. 

See also: @{"Record/Delete Record" link mnremoverecord} 
@endnode 


@node mncutrecord "Record/Cut Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Cut Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} X

Copies the current record to the clipboard and removes it from the record 
list of it's project. After that, you may use @{"Record/Paste Record" Link MnPasteRecord} to 
insert it in the project, again. 

    This function may only be called in record mode. 

See also: @{"Record/Copy Record" link mncopyrecord}, @{"Record/Paste Record" link mnpasterecord}, Section Clipboard 
support of Fiasco 
@endnode 


@node mncopyrecord "Record/Copy Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Copy Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} C

Copies the current record to the clipboard. After that, you may use 
@{"Record/Paste Record" link MnPasteRecord} to insert it in the project again. 

    This function may only be called in record mode. 

See also: @{"Record/Cut Record" link mncutrecord}, @{"Record/Paste Record" link mnpasterecord}, Section Clipboard 
support of Fiasco 
@endnode 


@node mnpasterecord "Record/Paste Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Paste Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} P

Creates a new record and pastes the contents of the clipboard into that 
record. Normally, you should call @{"Record/Cut Record" Link MnCutRecord} or @{"Record/Copy Record" Link MnCopyRecord} 
before calling this function. 

    This function may only be called in record mode. 

See also: @{"Record/Cut Record" link mncutrecord}, @{"Record/Copy Record" link mncopyrecord}, Section Clipboard 
support of Fiasco 
@endnode 


@node mnprevious "Record/Previous" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Previous@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: Cursor up

Activates the record, which is the predecessor of the current. If the 
current record is the first one, the display will be "beeped". Please 
note, that @{"Filters" link Filter} change the behavior of this item. In this case, the 
previous matching record will be activated. 

    The keyboardshortcut correspondents to the structure of the list, 
which displays the previous record over the current. 

    This menuitem may be only selected, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active. 

See also: @{"Next" link MnNext}, @{"First" link MnFirstRecord}, @{"Last" link MnLastRecord}, @{"Goto" link MnGoto}, @{"Find previous" link MnFindPrevious} 

@endnode 
@node mnnext "Record/Next" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Next@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: Cursor down

Activates the record after the current record. If the current record is 
the last in the list, the display will be "beeped". Please note, that 
@{"Filters" link Filter} change the behavior of this item. In the case of an active 
filter, the next matching record will be searched. 

    The keyboardshortcut correspondents to the structure of the list, 
which displays the next record under the current. 

    This menuitem may be only selected, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active. 

See also: @{"Previous" link MnPrevious}, @{"First" link MnFirstRecord}, @{"Last" link MnLastRecord}, @{"Goto" link MnGoto}, @{"Find next" link MnFindNext} 

@endnode 
@node mnfirstrecord "Record/First Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/First Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: Ctrl Cursor up

Activates the first record of the current project. In the case of an 
active @{"Filter" link Filter}, for the first matching record will be searched. 

    This item is only in the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} selectable. 

See also: @{"Next" link MnNext}, @{"Previous" link MnPrevious}, @{"Last" link MnLastRecord}, @{"Goto" link MnGoto} 
@endnode 
@node mnlastrecord "Record/Last Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Last Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: Ctrl Cursor down

Activates the last record of the current project. In the case of an 
active @{"Filter" link Filter}, for the last matching record will be searched. 

    This item may be only selected in the @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Next" link MnNext}, @{"Previous" link MnPrevious}, @{"First" link MnFIrstRecord}, @{"Goto" link MnGoto} 
@endnode 
@node mngoto "Record/Goto..." 

@{b}@{u}Record/Goto...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} G

Opens the @{"goto requester" link RqGoto}, which can be used to activate a record using 
it`s number. Please note, that the record number may be changed by adding 
or deleting records or by using @{"filters" link Filter}. 

    This item can only be selected in the @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Next" link MnNext}, @{"Previous" link MnPrevious}, @{"First" link MnFirstRecord}, @{"Last" link MnLastRecord} 

@endnode 
@node mnmarkrecord "Record/Mark Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Mark Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} .

Marks the current record. If a record is marked, it will displayed 
highlighted in the list and the character "M" will be displayed in the 
service window. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Unmark Record" link MnUnmarkRecord}, @{"Mark all Records" link MnMarkAllRecords}, @{"Unmark all Records" link MnUnmarkAllRecords} 
@endnode 
@node mnunmarkrecord "Record/Unmark Record" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Unmark Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} :

Deletes the mark of the current record. It won`t be displayed highlighted 
anymore. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Mark Record" link MnMarkRecord}, @{"Mark all Records" link MnMarkAllRecords}, @{"Unmark all Records" link MnUnmarkAllRecords} 
@endnode 


@node mnmarkallrecords "Record/Mark all Records" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Mark all Records@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} ,

Marks all records in the current project. Note, that the previous marking 
of all records will be overwritten. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Mark Record" link MnmarkRecord}, @{"Unmark Record" link MnUnmarkRecord}, @{"Unmark all Records" link MnUnMarkAllRecords}, @{"Toggle all Marks" link MnToggleAllMarks}
 
@endnode 


@node mnunmarkallrecords "Record/Unmark all Records" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Unmark all Records@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} ;

Clears the marks of all records in the current project. Note, that the 
previous marking of all records will be overwritten. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Mark Record" link MnmarkRecord}, @{"Unmark Record" link MnUnmarkRecord}, @{"Mark all Records" link MnMarkAllRecords}, @{"Toggle all Marks" link MnToggleAllMarks} 
@endnode 
@node mntoggleallmarks "Record/Toggle all Marks" 

@{b}@{u}Record/Toggle all Marks@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

Toggles the marks of all records in the current project. That means, that 
a marked record will get unmarked and an unmarked will get marked. You 
can restore the previous marking of the records by calling this menuitem 
again. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Mark Record" link MnmarkRecord}, @{"Unmark Record" link MnUnmarkRecord}, @{"Mark all Records" link MnMarkAllRecords}, @{"Unmark all Records" link MnUnmarkAllRecords}
 
@endnode 


@node mnfieldtype "Field/Fieldtype" 

@{b}@{u}Field/Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

Select in this submenu the current fieldtype. It will be used, if you 
create fields. The gadget at the bottom of the @{"service window" Link ServiceWin} has the 
same function.  These fieldtypes are available (with Shortcut): 


@{"String    " link FT_Str    }  Ctrl S 
@{"Integer   " link FT_Int    }  Ctrl I 
@{"Float     " link FT_Float  }  Ctrl F 
@{"Boolean   " link FT_Bool   }  Ctrl B 
@{"Cycle     " link FT_Cyc    }  Ctrl C 
@{"Slider    " link FT_Sld    }  Ctrl S 
@{"Date      " link FT_Date   }  Ctrl A 
@{"Time      " link FT_Time   }  Ctrl M 
@{"Extern    " link FT_Ext    }  Ctrl E 
@{"Datatypes " link FT_DT     }  Ctrl D 
@{"Text      " link FT_Txt    }  Ctrl T 
@{"Button    " link FT_Button }  Ctrl U 
@endnode 
@node mnaddfield "Field/Add Field..." 

@{b}@{u}Field/Add Field...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: Return

Opens the @{"field requester" Link RqEditField} for the current field type and inserts the 
created field at the current cursorposition. 

    This item can only be selected in the @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

    If there is already a field at the current cursor position, nothing 
will be done. 

    Please note, that Return is also shortcut for @{"Edit Field" link MnEditField}. Enter 
creates a new field, if no field is currently active, otherwise, it opens 
the requester for editing the current field. 

See also: @{"Edit Field" link MnEditField}, @{"Edit Relations" link MnEditRelations}, @{"Remove Field" link MnRemoveField} 
@endnode 


@node mneditfield "Field/Edit Field..." 

@{b}@{u}Field/Edit Field...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: Return

Opens the @{"field requester" Link RqEditField} for the selected field. The field requester can 
be used to change several attributes of the field. If certain changes 
would cause loose of data (e.g. changing max chars of a string field to a 
low number), you will be informed about the problem and have to 
possibility to cancel the change. Field types may not be changed this 
way. You have to use @{"Convert Field" Link MnConvertField}. 

    Please note, that Return is also a shortcut for @{"Add Field" link MnAddField}. Return 
calls Add Field, if no field is active, and otherwise Edit Field. 

    This item can only be selected in the @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{"Add Field" link MnAddField}, @{"Edit Relation" link MnEditRelations} 
@endnode 


@node mnduplicatefield "Field/Duplicate Field" 

@{b}@{u}Field/Duplicate Field@{ub}@{uu}

No shortcut
Makes an exact copy of the active field. It will be placed as near as 
possible to the original field. The ID will be copy_of_@{i}FieldID@{ui}. 
@endnode 
@node mnremovefield "Field/Remove Field" 

@{b}@{u}Field/Remove Field@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: Del

Removes the selected field. All data in this field will be also lost. 
Relations or ARexx scripts, which refer to this field, will be not 
functional. @{i}Attention: @{ui}The relations or ARexx scripts will not complain 
immediately after removing the field, but at the first activation. 

    This item can only be selected in the @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{"Edit Field" link MnEditField}, @{"Edit Relations" link MnEditRelations}, @{"Add Field" link MnAddField} 
@endnode 
@node mneditrelations "Field/Edit Relation..." 

@{b}@{u}Field/Edit Relation...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} &

This item opens the @{"relation requester" Link RqRel}, which adds a @{"relation" Link Relations} to the 
current field. 

    This item can only be selected in the @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{"Field/Remove Relation" link mnremoverelation} 
@endnode 
@node mnremoverelation "Field/Remove Relation" 

@{b}@{u}Field/Remove Relation@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} 0

This item deletes all relation informations of the active field. After 
that, the data in this field will be written into the normal file. 

    This item can only be selected in the @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

@endnode  
@node mnconvertfield "Field/Convert Field..." 

@{b}@{u}Field/Convert Field...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} "

Opens the @{"convert requester" Link RqConvertfield} for the selected field. Using convert, you 
may change the type of a field in a smart way. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{"Add Field" link MnAddField}, @{"Edit Field" link MnEditField} 
@endnode 


@node mnhidecolumn "List/Hide column" 

@{b}@{u}List/Hide column@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} [

Hides a activated column of the @{"List" link List}. You activate a column by clicking 
in the topmost line of the list, which contains the field IDs. After 
hiding a column, the columns at the right side of it will be shifted to 
the left. The column may be made visible again by using @{"Show column" Link MnShowColumn}. 

    This item may only be selected, if the list window is open. 

@endnode 
@node mnshowcolumn "List/Show column..." 

@{b}@{u}List/Show column...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} ]

This item opens a requester, which may be used to reveal the columns, 
which have been hidden with @{"Hide column" Link MnHideColumn}. Fiasco tries to place the 
columns as near as possible at their old positions. 

    This item may only be selected, if the list window is open. 

@endnode 
@node mnshowallcols "List/Show all columns" 

@{b}@{u}List/Show all columns@{ub}@{uu}

no shortcut

Makes all columns, which have been hidden using @{"Hide column" Link MnHideColumn}, visible 
again. 

    This item may only be selected, if the list window is open. 

@endnode 
@node mnrecalclist "List/Recalc List" 

@{b}@{u}List/Recalc List@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} %

This menuitem calculates all positions and dimensions of the columns in 
the @{"list" link list}. Hidden columns are not revealed. 

    This item can be compared with Clean up of the Workbench. 

    This item may only be selected, if the list window is open. 
@endnode 
@node mnfind "Compare/Find..." 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Find...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} F

Opens the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}, which can be used to define search 
criterions. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

See also: @{"search requester" link RqFind}, @{"Find next" link MnFindNext}, @{"Find previous" link MnFindPrevious} 
@endnode 


@node mnfindnext "Compare/Find next" 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Find next@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} >

Activates the @{i}next @{ui}record, which matches with the search criterions, 
which have been specified using the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}. If no matching 
record is found, you will be informed about that. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

See also: @{"Search requester" link RqFind}, @{"Find" link MnFind}, @{"Find previous" link MnFindPrevious} 
@endnode 


@node mnfindprevious "Compare/Find previous" 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Find previous@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} <

Activates the @{i}previous @{ui}record, which matches with the searchcriterions, 
which have been specified with the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}. If no record is 
found, you will be informed about that. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

See also: @{"Search requester" link RqFind}, @{"Find..." link MnFind}, @{"Find next" link MnFindNext} 
@endnode 
@node mnreplace "Compare/Replace..." 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Replace...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} R

Opens the @{"replace requester" Link RqReplace}, which can be used for replacing data. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

@endnode 
@node mncount "Compare/Count..." 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Count...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} #

Opens the @{"count requester" Link RqCount}, which can be used to determine the number of 
the records matching with the specified pattern. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

    See also: @{"Find" link MnFind} 
@endnode 
@node mnsort "Compare/Sort..." 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Sort...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} =

Opens the @{"sort requester" Link RqSort}, which may be used to sort the records of the 
current project. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 
@endnode 
@node mneditfilter "Compare/Edit Filter..." 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Edit Filter...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} 

Opens the @{"filter requester" Link RqFilter}, which can be used to create @{"Filters" link Filter}. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

@endnode 
@node mnusefilter "Compare/Use Filter?" 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Use Filter?@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} ` (Gray key at the upper left of the keyboard)

This item can be used to switch the @{"filter" Link filter} on or off. If no filter has 
been created yet, the @{"filter requester" Link RqFilter} will be opened. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

@endnode 
@node mnmark "Compare/Mark..." 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Mark...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} K

Opens the @{"mark requester" Link RqMark}, which can be used to mark specific records, 
which match a pattern. This works much like the creation of filters. 

    Existing marks will be overwritten; marked records will be unmarked, 
if they not match. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

@endnode 
@node mnfiltertomarks "Compare/Filter to Marks" 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Filter to Marks@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

Converts the current @{"filter" Link Filter} (active or inactive) to marks. Records, which 
match the filter, will be marked and records, which don`t match the 
filter, will be not marked. If the filter is active, it will be 
deactivated. 

See also: @{"Compare/Edit Filter" link MnEditFilter}, @{"Compare/Marks to Filter" link MnMarksToFilter} 
@endnode 


@node mnmarkstofilter "Compare/Marks to Filter" 

@{b}@{u}Compare/Marks to Filter@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

Converts the marking of the current project into a @{"filter" Link Filter}. Each marked 
record will be declared as valid record, every record, which is not 
marked, will be filtered out. This filter will not be copied into the 
filter requester. If you open the filter requester and proceed with Ok, 
the filter created with Marks to Filter will be overwritten. 

See also: @{"Compare/Filter to Marks" link MnFilterToMarks} 
@endnode 


@node mnrecordmode "Control/Record Mode" 

@{b}@{u}Control/Record Mode@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} D

This item switches the current project to @{"record mode" Link RecordMode}, in which records 
and the contents of records can be changed. If this mode is @{i}active @{ui}, a 
checkmark will be set at the left side of the item. 

See also: @{"Record mode" link RecordMode}, @{"Mask mode" link MaskMode} 
@endnode 


@node mnmaskmode "Control/Mask Mode" 

@{b}@{u}Control/Mask Mode@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} M

This item switches the current project to @{"mask mode" Link MaskMode}, in which the @{"mask" link mask} 
can be changed. If this mode is @{i}active @{ui}, a checkmark will be set at the 
left side of the item. 

See also: @{"Mask mode" link MaskMode}, @{"Record mode" link RecordMode} 

@endnode 
@node mnservicewindow "Control/ServiceWindow" 

@{b}@{u}Control/ServiceWindow@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} W

This item controls the @{"service window" Link ServiceWin}. If it is checked, the service 
window is open. The service window makes the most important record- and 
mask-operations easier and displays some status information. 

    The service window serves globally for all projects. 
@endnode 
@node mnlistwindow "Control/ListWindow" 

@{b}@{u}Control/ListWindow@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} L

This item controls the @{"list window" link List}, if it is checked, the list is open. 

    Each project may have it`s own list window. 
@endnode 
@node mnarexxdebug "Control/ARexx-Debug" 

@{b}@{u}Control/ARexx-Debug@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} B

This activates a special debug mode of Fiasco for the @{"ARexx interface" link ARexx}. If 
Fiasco commands fail, Fiasco will create an requester, which contains 
more detailed informations about the error. 

@endnode 
@node mncreateicons "Settings/Create Icons?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Create Icons?@{ub}@{uu}

If this item is checked, Fiasco will create icons while saving projects. 
@endnode 
@node mncreatebackup "Settings/Create Backups?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Create Backups?@{ub}@{uu}

This item determines, whether Fiasco creates backups of old projects 
while saving new projects. The backup file will be named @{i}oldname@{ui}.bak.  
@endnode 
@node mnwriterelations "Settings/Write Relations?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Write Relations?@{ub}@{uu}

If this item is checked, Fiasco will also write relations back in their 
"there" projects. Otherwise, changes made in these fields will be lost. 
This item should be only active, if @{"Update Relations?" Link MnUpdateRelations} is also active, or 
if you call @{"Project/Reload Rels" Link MnReloadRels} before saving. Otherwise you risk, that 
data in the "there" project will be overwritten by invalid data in some 
fields of the "here" project. 
@endnode 
@node mnupdaterelations "Settings/Update Rels?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Update Rels?@{ub}@{uu}

This item determines, whether @{"relations" link Relations} are updated immediately after the 
input of a new key. This requires disk accesses, which may become 
annoying if Fiasco has to read the data from a floppy disk. If you 
deactivate this item, you should also deactivate @{"Write relations?" Link MnWriteRelations}, 
because there may be invalid data in the project, which would be written 
into the "there" file. If you want to see the changes, you can update the 
relations using @{"Project/Reload Rels" Link MnReloadRels}.  
@endnode 
@node mnstarpattern "Settings/Use * as Pattern?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Use * as Pattern?@{ub}@{uu}

Activate this item to activate the support of the asterisk as a valid 
searchpattern. The * has then the same meaning as #?. 
@endnode 


@node mnsecurityrequester "Settings/Security-Reqs?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Security-Reqs?@{ub}@{uu}

If this item is checked, Fiasco will warn you before deleting any fields 
or records. This can prevent erroneous deleting and loss of data. 
@endnode 
@node mnautoopenservicewin "Settings/Auto-Open ServiceWin?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Auto-Open ServiceWin?@{ub}@{uu}

If this item is checked, the @{"service window" Link ServiceWin} will be opened on every 
program start automatically. 
@endnode 
@node mndynamicservicewin "Settings/Dynamic ServiceWin?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Dynamic ServiceWin?@{ub}@{uu}

If this item is checked, the @{"service window" link ServiceWin} will be opened at an free 
place. Otherwise, fixed coordinates will be used. 
@endnode 
@node mntalking "Settings/Talking?" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Talking?@{ub}@{uu}

Check this item, if you want Fiasco to use the narrator.device to "speak" 
certain messages. 
@endnode 
@node mndisplay "Settings/Display..." 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Display...@{ub}@{uu}

no shortcut

Opens the @{"display requester" link rqdisplayopts}, which can be used to specify display options 
for Fiasco. You can select here, whether Fiasco shall open it's windows 
on a public screen or on an own custom screen. Furthermore, you may 
select fonts for the screen and the mask. 

    The latter replaces the menuitem Settings/Choose Font of Fiasco 1.0. 

@endnode 
@node mneditor "Settings/Editor..." 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Editor...@{ub}@{uu}

no shortcut

Opens a requester, which lets you specify a editor program, which will be 
called by Fiasco, if you select the Edit Script button in the 
fieldrequesters. 

@endnode 
@node mnsavesettings "Settings/Save Settings" 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Save Settings@{ub}@{uu}

Saves the current program settings in the files "env:fiasco.prefs" and 
"envarc:fiasco.prefs". The settings "survive" rebooting. 
@endnode 
@node mnsavesettingsas "Settings/Save Settings as..." 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Save Settings as...@{ub}@{uu}

Saves the settings in a file, which has been specified with an ASL 
requester. If you save the file in "env:", the settings won`t survive an 
reboot. If you save them only in "envarc:", they will get first active 
after rebooting, because Fiasco searches for it`s current settings only 
in "env:". 
@endnode 
@node mnloadsettings "Settings/Load Settings..." 

@{b}@{u}Settings/Load Settings...@{ub}@{uu}

Loads a specified settings file and uses them. To use them also after 
reboots, you should select @{"Save Settings" link MnSaveSettings} to write them to "env:" and 
"envarc:". 
@endnode 
@node mneditum "User/Edit..." 

@{b}@{u}User/Edit...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}U

Opens the @{"Usermenu requester" Link RqEditUserMenu}, which can be used to define Usermenus. 

@endnode 
@node Requester "All requesters" 

@{b}@{u}All requesters@{ub}@{uu}

Requesters are used by Fiasco to get information, that is required for 
certain operations. Normally, the requesters are created after selecting 
a menuitem of Fiasco. So called EasyRequesters, which are used by fiasco 
to request a simple choice are not explained here, because they are 
mostly easy to understand and described in function specific sections. 

    Most requesters can be controlled by using the keyboard. The 
shortcuts, which are marked with an underscore, are usually single 
characters without a qualifier. 

    The gadgets at the lower bottom of a requester are usually for 
proceeding. Normally, the leftmost is a positive response (Ok), while the 
rightmost is a negative response (Cancel). The positive response, which 
has an additional frame, has Enter as shortcut. The negative has Escape 
as shortcut. 

@{"Edit Field     " link RqEditField  }
@{"Convert field  " link RqConvertField}
@{"Find           " link RqFind       }
@{"Replace        " link RqReplace    }
@{"Count          " link RqCount      }
@{"Sort           " link RqSort       }
@{"Filter         " link RqFilter     }
@{"Mark           " link RqMark       }
@{"Usermenu       " link RqEditUserMenu}
@{"Options        " link RqOptions    }
@{"Goto           " link RqGoto       }
@{"Edit Relation  " link RqRel        }
@{"Show column    " link RqShowColumn }
@{"Display Options" link RqDisplayOpts}
@{"Import         " link RqImport     }
@{"Export         " link RqExport     }
@endnode 
@node rqeditfield "Field requester" 

@{b}@{u}Field requester@{ub}@{uu}

The field requester can be used to change the attributes of a field. Each 
fieldtype has a different field requester, because the gadgets of the 
field requester represent the supported attributes of each fieldtype. The 
supported attributes are listed with the @{"field documentations" link FieldTypes}. The field 
requester will show up, if you call @{"Add Field" Link MnAddField}, @{"Edit Field" Link MnEditField} or doubleclick 
on a field. 

    If you proceed with Ok, all values will be checked for validity.  If 
one value cannot be used by Fiasco, a requester will explain the problem. 

    @{b}A small summary of the conditions:@{ub} (presumed, that these attributes 
exist)

@{b}·@{ub}  There must be an Id. 

@{b}·@{ub}  MaxChars must be > 0. 

@{b}·@{ub}  Width must be > 2. 
If dimensionvalues cannot be used, because other fields are too near 
at the field, another requester appears, which has the gadgets Shift, 
Squeeze and Cancel. Cancel does nothing, it only returns to the field 
requester. Squeeze makes the field fitting in the space. Shift shifts the 
field to the left, to make it fitting. It is not always possible to Shift
.  

    If you change a already existing field, which stores it`s contents in 
strings and supports MaxChars (currently @{"String" link FT_Str}, @{"Extern" link FT_Ext} and @{"Datatypes" link FT_DT}), 
an additional control is implemented. If you change "MaxChars" to a 
value, which does not allow to keep all strings in their original length 
(that means, some strings are longer), you will be asked, whether you 
really want to cut these strings or to keep the old value. 

@endnode 
@node rqconvertfield "Convert Field requester" 

@{b}@{u}Convert Field requester@{ub}@{uu}

The convert field requester can be used to change the type of one field 
without the need of an ARexx script. 

@{b}Field ID: @{ub}  This text gadget displays the ID of the field, which will be 
   converted. Please check here, whether you have called Convert Field 
   for the correct field.  

@{b}old Type: @{ub}  Displays the current type of the field.  

@{b}new Type: @{ub}  Select here the new type of the field. Please note, that 
   conversions between certain fieldtypes may loose data. Consult the 
   @{"field documentation" link FieldTypes} for more information on this topic.  

@{b}alternative format: @{ub}  Select this checkbox to active an output-format, 
   which differs from the normal format. Please see the @{"field docs" link FieldTypes}, 
   whether this gadget has any effect and if, what effect.  

@{b}Ok:  @{ub}  Starts the conversion and exits then.  

@{b}Cancel:  @{ub} Simply closes the requester.  

@endnode 
@node rqfind "Search requester" 

@{b}@{u}Search requester@{ub}@{uu}


@{b}Field: @{ub}  Select here the field, which will be searched. The listview 
   displays only the ids of real fields, buttons and textfields are not 
   displayed. Only one field can be selected.  

@{b}Pattern: @{ub}  Enter here the pattern to search. It may be a simple value or 
   one with @{"Patterns" link Patterns}. This value will be also used in the count and 
   replace requesters.  

@{b}Blurred search/Activated: @{ub}  If you want to use @{"``blurred search''" Link BlurredSearch}, you 
   will have to activate this gadget.  

@{b}Blurred search/factor: @{ub}  You can control here the tolerance of the 
   "blurred search". 0 searches only for exactly matching entries, 100 
   searches for almost all entries.  

@{b}Next: @{ub}  Proceeds with searching for the next matching entry and activates 
   it.  

@{b}First: @{ub}  Searches for the first matching entry.  

@{b}Previous: @{ub}  Searches backwards for the next matching entry.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub}  Closes the requester without any further action.  

@endnode 
@node rqreplace "Replace requester" 

@{b}@{u}Replace requester@{ub}@{uu}

If you already know the @{"search requester" link RqFind}, you should have no problems 
with this one. 

@{b}Field: @{ub}  Select here the field, which will be searched. The listview 
   displays only the ids of fields, textfields are not displayed. Only 
   one field can be selected.  

@{b}Pattern: @{ub}  Enter here the pattern to search. It may be a simple value or 
   one with @{"Patterns" link Patterns}. This value will be also used in the count and 
   replace requesters.  

@{b}Replacement: @{ub}  Enter here a value, which will be copied in the matching 
   entries. No patterns are possible.  

@{b}Confirm: @{ub}  If you want to be asked for every replacing operation, you 
   should select this gadget.  

@{b}Blurred search/Activated: @{ub}  If you want to use @{"blurred search" link BlurredSearch}, you will 
   have to activate this gadget.  

@{b}Blurred search/factor: @{ub}  You can control here the tolerance of the 
   blurred search. 0 searches only for exactly matching entries, 100 
   searches for almost all entries.  

@endnode 
@node rqcount "Count requester" 

@{b}@{u}Count requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester lets you count records, which match with a patterns. More 
on counting @{"here" link Count}.        You can open this requester using @{"Compare/Count" Link MnCount}. 

    If you already know the @{"search requester" link RqFind}, you should have no problems 
with this one. 

    
@{b}Field: @{ub}  Select here the field, which will be searched. The listview 
   displays only the ids of fields, textfields are not displayed. Only 
   one field can be selected.  

@{b}Pattern: @{ub}  Enter here the pattern to search. It may be a simple value or 
   one with @{"Patterns" link Patterns}. This value will be also used in the search and 
   replace requesters.  

@{b}Blurred search/Activated: @{ub}  If you want to use @{"blurred search" link BlurredSearch}, you will 
   have to activate this gadget.  

@{b}Blurred search/factor: @{ub}  You can control here the tolerance of the 
   blurred search. 0 searches only for exactly matching entries, 100 
   searches for almost all entries.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub}  proceeds and counts the matching records. The number will be 
   displayed at the end.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub}  closes the requester without any further action.  

@endnode 
@node rqsort "Sort requester" 

@{b}@{u}Sort requester@{ub}@{uu}

You can sort a Fiasco project in the sort requester in respect to one 
field. It can be opened using @{"Compare/Sort" Link MnSort}. 

@{b}Sort by: @{ub}  A list of all fields is displayed here. You should select a 
   field here, which will be used as orientation while searching.  

@{b}Descending: @{ub}  Select this gadget to sort the data from high values to low 
   values (i.e. Z, Y, X, ..., C, B, A)  

@{b}Ok: @{ub}  begins with sorting. The previously active record will be kept 
   active, but it is highly probable, that the number of the record will 
   change.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub}  Closes the requester without any further action.  

@endnode 
@node rqfilter "Filter requester" 

@{b}@{u}Filter requester@{ub}@{uu}

@{"Filters" Link Filter} offer the possibility to create an overview over a group of 
records. A filter creates the impression of a database, which consists 
only of the matching records. Filters are not created during the normal 
program functions, but it is created immediately after confirming the 
filter requester. That means, records which will be added to project, 
during a filter is active, will be displayed regardless of their 
contents. The same rules for changes records. The filter requester may be 
reached using @{"Compare/Edit Filter" link MnEditFilter}. 

    If you already know the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}, you should have no problems 
with this one. 

    
@{b}Field: @{ub}  Select here the field, which will be searched. The listview 
   displays only the ids of fields, textfields are not displayed. Only 
   one field can be selected.  

@{b}Pattern: @{ub}  Enter here the pattern to search. It may be a simple value or 
   one with @{"Patterns" link Patterns}.  

@{b}Blurred search/Activated: @{ub}  If you want to use @{"blurred search" link BlurredSearch}, you will 
   have to activate this gadget.  

@{b}Blurred search/factor: @{ub}  You can control here the tolerance of the 
   blurred search. 0 searches only for exactly matching entries, 100 
   searches for almost all entries.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub}  creates the filter. The project will seem, as if would consist only 
   of matching records.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub}  closes the requester without any further action.  

@endnode 
@node rqmark "Mark requester" 

@{b}@{u}Mark requester@{ub}@{uu}

The mark function of Fiasco provides a possibility to remember about a 
specific record. The mark requester has the purpose to mark all records, 
which match with a specific pattern. This requester is highly related to 
the filter and @{"search requesters" Link RqFind}. The mark requester may be opened with 
@{"Compare/Mark" link MnMark}. 

    
@{b}Field: @{ub}  Select here the field, which will be searched. The listview 
   displays only the ids of fields, textfields are not displayed. Only 
   one field can be selected.  

@{b}Pattern: @{ub}  Enter here the pattern to search. It may be a simple value or 
   one with @{"Patterns" link Patterns}.  

@{b}Blurred search/Activated: @{ub}  If you want to use @{"blurred search" link BlurredSearch}, you will 
   have to activate this gadget.  

@{b}Blurred search/factor: @{ub}  You can control here the tolerance of the 
   blurred search. 0 searches only for exactly matching entries, 100 
   searches for almost all entries.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub}  marks the matching records. The old marking of the records will be 
   lost!  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub}  closes the requester without any further action.  

@endnode 
@node rqeditusermenu "Usermenu requester" 

@{b}@{u}Usermenu requester@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco has the ability to create own menuitems and to put CLI programs or 
ARexx scripts behind them. The defined items may be selected apart from 
the classic way with the mouse with the F-Keys. F1 to F10 correspondent 
to the first ten items, Shift and F1 to F10 correspondent to the items 11 
to 20. If you want to define more than 20 items, you will have to select 
the additional items with the mouse. Furthermore, Intuition limits the 
number of definable items to 63. If you try to define more items, they 
will be cut. 

    The items may be saved using @{"Settings/Save Settings" Link MnSaveSettings}. 

    
@{b}Items: @{ub}  This is the list of all existing menu items. With Add you 
   can add one, with Del you can delete one and < and > serve to change 
   the position of the item.  

@{b}Type: @{ub}  Select here, whether you want to call a program or a ARexx 
   script.  

@{b}Command: @{ub}  Select here the program or the ARexx script respectively, 
   which shall be executed.  

@endnode 
@node rqoptions "Option requester" 

@{b}@{u}Option requester@{ub}@{uu}

The option requester contains settings, which concern the project. It may 
be opened using the menuitem @{"Project/Options" link MnOptions} or the ARexx command 
@{"F_OptionsReq" link F_OptionsReq}. 

@{b}Name: @{ub}  Here you can change the filename of the project. The project will 
   be saved under this name in future. After saving, all 
   direction-relative operations will use the new directory.  

@{b}Author: @{ub}  You can use this field to enter your own Name! It will be 
   stored at the beginning of the project file.   

@{b}Annotations: @{ub}  Yet another gadget for free use. You may store any notes 
   here, for example a version string (with $VER: at the beginning). It 
   will be written to the project file just before the author.   

@{b}stretch  X / Y: @{ub}  These values are added to the with or height of the 
   cursor. The effect of this operation is a stretching of the mask in X- 
   or Y-direction.  More on stretching @{"here" link stretch}.        

@endnode 
@node rqgoto "Goto requester" 

@{b}@{u}Goto requester@{ub}@{uu}

The goto requester is one of the simplest requesters in Fiasco at all. It 
may be opened with @{"Record/Goto" link MnGoto} and offers the possibility to activate a 
record using it`s number. Please note, that @{"Filters" link Filter} change the record 
numbers. 

    
@{b}go to: @{ub}  Takes the number of the record.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub}  Proceeds and activates the record with the number.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub}  Oh sorry, i just forgot... %-) 

@endnode 
@node rqrel "Relation requester" 

@{b}@{u}Relation requester@{ub}@{uu}

This is the main interface for @{"relation" Link Relations} handling in Fiasco. It may be 
opened using @{"Field/Edit Relations" link MnEditRelations}. 

@{b}Key here: @{ub}  Select here the key in the current project.  

@{b}Real here: @{ub}  displays the ID of the field, whose relations are just now 
   edited.  

@{b}Key there: @{ub}  Select here the field of the project, which has been 
   specified under Related File, which contains the Key. This listview 
   displays only fields, which can contain the Key (with same type).  

@{b}Real there: @{ub}  Select here the field of the project, which has been 
   specified under Related File, which is supposed to be the counterpart 
   of Real here. This field is used to read the Data, which will be 
   displayed in Real here. This listview displays also only fields, which 
   look as if they could contain the data (type and max chars must be 
   equal).  

@{b}Related File: @{ub}  Select here the project file relative to the directory of 
   the current project, which contains the informations.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub}  Proceeds with loading the relations. If any errors occur while 
   loading, the requester will be activated again, otherwise it will 
   return to the main window.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub}  closes the requester without any further action.  

@endnode 
@node rqshowcolumn "Show column requester" 

@{b}@{u}Show column requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester, which may be reached with @{"List/Show column" link MnShowColumn}, displays the 
currently hidden columns in the @{"list" link list}. If you select one and click on Ok, 
the column will be inserted in the list at it`s old position. 

@{b}Field: @{ub}  All hidden columns are displayed here. Select here the column, 
   which you want to be revealed.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub}  Inserts the column and redisplays the list.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub}  Closes the requester.  

@endnode 
@node rqdisplayopts "Display Options Requester" 

@{b}@{u}Display Options Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester controls the display elements of Fiasco. You can open an 
own screen for Fiasco and choose the fonts for the custom screen and for 
the mask (Fiasco 1.0 had the menuitem Choose Font for this purpose). 

@{b}Screen @{ub} 

@{b}Screentype: @{ub} Select here, whether you want to use a public screen or an 
   own custom screen.  

@{b}PubScreen Name: @{ub} Specify here the name of the public screen, you want 
   Fiasco to open it's windows on it. This has only effect, if you select 
   at Screentype the choice PublicScreen. If you leave this gadget empty, 
   Fiasco will use the default public screen.  

@{b}Screen Mode: @{ub} You may select here the display mode for the custom screen. 
   Clicking on the popup gadget will open an ASL screenmode requester. 
   This requires asl.library version 38 or higher.   

@{b}Screen Font: @{ub} This gadget controls, whether you want to use an own font 
   for the custom screen or the Workbench screen font, which is 
   controlled by the Font Preferences.  

@{b}Custom Font: @{ub} If you want to use an own font for the custom screen, you 
   may select it here.  

@{b}Mask Font @{ub}   

@{b}Mask Font: @{ub} This gadget controls, whether you want to use an own font for 
   the mask or the System default font, which is controlled by the Font 
   Preferences.  

@{b}Custom Font: @{ub} You may select here an own font for the mask. It must be 
   fixed width.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub} Proceeds with resetting the display of Fiasco. If required, a new 
   screen is opened, and so on.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 

@endnode 
@node rqimport "Import requester" 

@{b}@{u}Import requester@{ub}@{uu}

The import requester is the GUI interface to the @{"import function" Link XPort} of 
Fiasco. Import makes Fiasco able to read data from other databases 
programs. Most times, this cannot be done directly, but the foreign 
database has to "export" the data. You may specify various parameters for 
importing, so you should be able to read nearly all 
import-/export-formats into Fiasco. 

    The Fiasco distribution contains several predefined import formats, 
which can be loaded using the Load button at the bottom of the import 
requester. 

    The values, that may be typed in the gadgets of the import requester, 
are described in the Import/Export section of this document. 

    
@{b}File: @{ub} Specify here the file, which contains the data to import. You 
   may use the picker button at the right side to select it using an ASL 
   requester.  

@{b}View: @{ub} Click here, if you want to view the contents of the file. Fiasco 
   will start asynchronously More or MultiView, if available.  

@{b}Records/Start: @{ub} Enter here the start characters for records. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Records/End: @{ub} Enter here the characters at the end of a record. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Records/Separator: @{ub} Enter here the characters between two records. 
   Default: \\n.  

@{b}Fields/Start: @{ub} Enter here the characters, fields start with. Default: ".  

@{b}Fields/End: @{ub} Enter here the characters, fields end with. Default: ".  

@{b}Fields/Separator: @{ub} Enter here the characters between two fields. Default: 
   \\t.  

@{b}Misc/Skip Lines: @{ub} Enter here introducing characters for remarks. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Misc/Start skip: @{ub} Enter here the number of lines, which shall be skipped 
   at the start. Default: 0.  

@{b}Misc/Max fields: @{ub} Enter here the maximum number of fields in a record. 
   Can also be used, if record separators are missing. Default: 100.  

@{b}Options/First record contains IDs: @{ub} Activate this gadget, if the first 
   record of the file contains the IDs of the fields in the project. They 
   will be used by Fiasco then instead of generic IDs.  

@{b}Options/Append new fields: @{ub} Activate this, if you want Fiasco to create 
   new fields for your data and not to use existing ones. If you have an 
   entirely empty project, you should activate this option.  

@{b}Options/Overwrite old project: @{ub} Removes the old data in the current 
   project window. If you do not select this, you data will be appended 
   somehow to the existing project.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub} Starts the import process. Note that Fiasco may run out of memory 
   due to bad structure parameters and too big files. Programs, which 
   have problems with low memory should not run during this process.  

@{b}Save: @{ub} Saves the current settings in a specified file.  

@{b}Load: @{ub} Reads the settings from a specified file and sets them up in the 
   requester.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 

@endnode 
@node rqexport "Export requester" 

@{b}@{u}Export requester@{ub}@{uu}

The export function provides a capability to share the data, which were 
created using Fiasco with other databases, which cannot read the normal 
format of Fiasco databases. See the @{"Import/Export section" link xport} of this 
document for more information about this mechanism. 

@{b}File: @{ub} Specify here the name of the file, the data shall be written to. 
   If a file already exists with this name, it will be overwritten.  

@{b}Records/Start: @{ub} Enter here the start characters for records. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Records/End: @{ub} Enter here the characters at the end of a record. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Records/Separator: @{ub} Enter here the characters between two records. 
   Default: \\n.  

@{b}Fields/Start: @{ub} Enter here the characters, fields start with. Default: ".  

@{b}Fields/End: @{ub} Enter here the characters, fields end with. Default: ".  

@{b}Fields/Separator: @{ub} Enter here the characters between two fields. Default: 
   \\t.  

@{b}Options/First record contains IDs: @{ub} Activate this gadget, if you want 
   Fiasco to write the field IDs in the first record.  

@{b}Options/Marked records only: @{ub} Activate this gadget, if you want Fiasco to 
   write only records, which are marked.  

@{b}Ok: @{ub} Click here to start the export process.  

@{b}Save: @{ub} Saves the structure parameters in a selected file.  

@{b}Load: @{ub} Loads the structure parameters in a selected file.  

@{b}Cancel: @{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 

@endnode 
@node AREXX "ARexx" 

@{b}@{u}ARexx@{ub}@{uu}

ARexx is a macro programming language, which is capable to connect 
different programs. ARexx has been developed by William S. Hawes and is 
part of the system software since OS 2.0.  

    The ARexx port of Fiasco may be accessed externally out of a script, 
or ARexx scripts can be called by Fiasco. For example. this happens if 
you specify in the field attribute @{"Script" link StdAttrs}  an ARexx script and you change 
the contents of a field. These scripts may react on the change and can 
adjust the value of another field or can do something else. 

    To be able to communicate with Fiasco, you have to add the line 
Address FIASCO to the script. 

    Nearly all operations, which can be used with the GUI of Fiasco, can 
be used with the ARexx commands. Additional, the functions of Fiasco may 
be extended with ARexx. There are many ARexx commands, which do exactly 
the same as their GUI "brothers". That means, that certain commands may 
open a requester under certain conditions. It is often possible to 
circumvent this problem. It will be fixed sometimes in the future. There 
are also commands, which open a requester in any case. This may be also 
useful for scripts, but has been primary implemented to give Fiasco a 
second menu (Iconbars). I have experimented already with 
ToolManager-Docks. Unfortunately, this was too slow for fast browsing in 
a database. 

@{"General facts about using ARexx with Fiasco" link ARexxGen }
@{"Index of all ARexx commands" link ARexxCmds } 
@endnode 
@node ARexxGen "ARexx and Fiasco in general" 

@{b}@{u}ARexx and Fiasco in general@{ub}@{uu}

A Fiasco command returns in the case of success in RC 0. If a command had 
problems, because it`s environment was not proper, 5 is returned. More 
serious errors, like missing arguments, return 10. Fatal errors return 
20. Parameter are separated by white spaces. If single arguments are 
supposed to contain spaces, it does not work to enclose them simply in 
quotation-marks. This is caused by ARexx, which swallows all 
quotation-marks. To avoid this, you should enclose the marks in the other 
marks. (e.g. F_Open ' "Test Datei" ')  You have to use the single quotes 
at the outer position, because Fiasco only handle double quotes. Be sure, 
not to use variables inside of any quotations. To use them, you have to 
close the quotation, write the variable and open the quotation again, if 
required. These issues do not apply for argument, which have the /F 
modifier. If a command returns a value, this is stored in RESULT. To use 
RESULT, you have to put an OPTIONS RESULTS at the beginning of a script.  

    The debugging of ARexx scripts is a bit problematic. Scripts, which 
have been activated using the user menu or fields, have no output stream. 
All errormessages will be swallowed. If you want to test ARexx scripts, 
you should run the scripts from the shell (using rx @{i}filename@{ui}; Fiasco must 
be in the correct status). To get more information, why a command failed, 
which has been sent to Fiasco, you should activate the item 
@{"Control/ARexx Debug" link MnARexxDebug}. Fiasco will show a requester with a explanation for 
the reason of the error. The script won`t continue until the requester 
has been closed. You have two choices there: Continue returns the correct 
error code, Ignore Error returns 0 in RC, which looks like the command 
has succeeded. An additional choice is Help, which won`t proceed, but 
display the help text for the command, which failed. 

    The style of the documentation of the commands is similar to the 
Amiga OS Autodocs. Synopsis defines a template. 

@{"Index of all ARexx commands" link ARexxCmds } 
@endnode 
