@node f_unmarkallrecords "F_UnmarkAllRecords" 

@{b}@{u}F_UnmarkAllRecords@{ub}@{uu}


@{b}Name: @{ub}  F_UnmarkAllRecords -- Clear the mark on all records.  

@{b}Synopsis: @{ub}  F_UnmarkRecord  

@{b}Function: @{ub}  Clears all marks of the records in the current project. They 
   will be rendered in a normal appearance in the list. Does exactly the 
   same as @{"Records/Unmark All" Link mnunmarkallrecords}.  

@{b}Inputs: @{ub}   

@{b}Results: @{ub}   

@{b}See also: @{ub}  @{"F_UnmarkRecord" link F_UnmarkRecord} @{"F_MarkAllRecords" link F_MarkAllRecords}  

@endnode 


@node f_unmarkrecord "F_UnmarkRecord" 

@{b}@{u}F_UnmarkRecord@{ub}@{uu}


@{b}Name: @{ub}  F_UnmarkRecord -- Clear the mark on a record  

@{b}Synopsis: @{ub}  F_UnmarkRecord Record/N  

@{b}Function: @{ub}  Clears the mark on a record, which has be set previously by 
   @{"F_MarkRecord" Link F_MarkRecord} or using the GUI. The record will be rendered in a 
   normal appearance in the list.  This command may be also called in 
   virtual state.  

@{b}Inputs: @{ub}  Record/N -- Optional number of record to unmark. If not given, 
   the current record will be unmarked.  

@{b}Results: @{ub}   

@{b}See also: @{ub}  @{"F_UnmarkAllRecords" link F_UnmarkAllRecords} @{"F_MarkRecord" link F_MarkRecord}  

@endnode 
@node f_usercommand "F_UserCommand" 

@{b}@{u}F_UserCommand@{ub}@{uu}


@{b}Name: @{ub}  F_UserCommand -- Calls a userdefined command.  

@{b}Synopsis: @{ub}  F_UserCommand Command/N/A  

@{b}Function: @{ub}  Calls a command, which has been defined in the "User" menu.  

@{b}Inputs: @{ub}  Command - Number of command, counted from zero. If this number 
   does not exits, nothing will be done.  

@{b}Results: @{ub}  none  

@{b}Note: @{ub}  This command is @{i}only@{ui} for implementing a icon bar or similar 
   things. It should not be used in normal scripts, because the command 
   may change freely.  

@{b}See also: @{ub}   

@endnode 


@node f_virtualmode "F_VirtualMode" 

@{b}@{u}F_VirtualMode@{ub}@{uu}


@{b}Name: @{ub} F_VirtualMode -- Is this script called from virtual mode? 

@{b}Synopsis: @{ub} F_VirtualMode rc = @{i}Virtual@{ui} 

@{b}Function: @{ub} Tests, whether the running script is called by Fiasco in 
   virtual mode or in normal mode. 

@{b}Inputs: @{ub}   

@{b}Results: @{ub} rc = 0: virtual status
   rc <> 0: normal status
   

@{b}See also: @{ub} Section virtual fields 


@endnode 
















@node EXAMPLES "Example Projects" 

@{b}@{u}Example Projects@{ub}@{uu}

The directory databases of the Fiasco distribution contains several 
Fiasco projects. Some of them may be also used for own purposes. 

@{"Addresses      " link DBAddresses} Addressbook 
@{"DatatypesDemo  " link DBDatatypesDemo} Demonstration of datatypes Fieldtype 
@{"FamilyTree     " link DBFamilyTree} stores data about you ancestors. 
@{"Videos         " link DBVideos} Catalog of video tapes 
@{"PictureDatabase" link DBPictures} Manages your pictures 
@{"FAQs           " link DBFaqs} Manages textfiles 
@endnode 
@node DBAddresses "Addresses" 

@{b}@{u}Addresses@{ub}@{uu}

The Address project can be used as a simple addressbook. It contains 
fields for Name, Address, Phone, etc. The project uses relations to 
translate the abbreviations of country names (like "I" for Italy) to the 
long names. 

    The fields for Phone, Fax or Zipcode are string fields, because they 
also have to take characters like "/" or must have a leading "0" (which 
would be swallowed by a integer field). 

    An additional Idea would be to use relations to search for the name 
of the city using the zip code. 
@endnode 
@node DBDatatypesDemo "Datatypes Demo" 

@{b}@{u}Datatypes Demo@{ub}@{uu}

This project is a easy Demonstration of the @{"Datatypes fieldtype" link FT_DT}, which 
requires the datatypes.library. For this reason, it is only available for 
users of Amiga OS 3.0 or higher. The mask contains three fields, which 
can be used to display all Data, which have the correct datatypes 
installed. 

    Two fields have scrollbars at the bottom and at the right side. You 
can use these scrollers to move the contents of the field. The 
stringgadget below the display contains the name of the file. The gadget 
with the arrow down at the left side of the string gadgets can be used to 
open a filerequester for editing the filename. 

    One field has a button marked with an `S'. This button opens a 
filerequester, which allows you to select a file, in which the currently 
displayed data are saved in. Fiasco writes the data in IFF format. 

    The field at the upper right has the `immediate play' attribute, 
which plays the data --- if playable --- directly after loading the data. 

    The browsing between records may get a bit slower, because the data 
are stored in an external file and must be loaded first. 
@endnode 
@node DBFamilyTree "FamilyTree" 

@{b}@{u}FamilyTree@{ub}@{uu}

The family tree consists of the projects "persons.fdb" and 
"families.fdb". "persons.fdb" contains all persons, which are used in the 
family tree. You may also enter sex, date of birth, etc. here. 

    These data are used by "families.fdb" with relations, to get names of 
spouses, children, etc. Additionally, there are fields for marriage and 
divorce. Caused by the intensive use of relations, this project only 
contains 10 "real" fields, which are stored on disk. The other 12 fields 
are loaded from "persons". 

@endnode 
@node DBVideos "Videos" 

@{b}@{u}Videos@{ub}@{uu}

The video database can be used to manage your homevideo collection. The 
database consists of two projects: "movies.fdb" and "tapes.fdb". "Movies" 
takes the informations for each movie (Genre, Director, etc.). The field 
"Tape" connects each film with one tape, which can be found in "tapes". 
Here is the play length of each tape defined. An ARexx script calculates 
the left free space on the tapes. 

@endnode 
@node DBPictures "Picture Database" 

@{b}@{u}Picture Database@{ub}@{uu}

This databases uses the Datatypes fieldtype and is only usable, if you 
have Amiga OS 3.0 or better. The Datatypes field has the "defer" 
attribute, which means, that Fiasco won`t load the data immediately. To 
read the data, you have to click in the string gadget of the field and 
press Return. 

    The string field under the datatypes field takes a description of the 
picture. 

    The button "Scan directory" can be used to read a freely selectable 
directory in the database. "Show on screen" displays the picture on an 
own screen. This button currently only works, if you use absolute paths 
for the graphics. 
@endnode 
@node DBFaqs "FAQs Database" 

@{b}@{u}FAQs Database@{ub}@{uu}

This database manages textfiles. For displaying the files, it uses the 
program Most by Uwe Röhm. If you prefer another textdisplay program, 
which has an ARexx port, you may adopt the ARexx scripts. 

    The string field at the top of the mask takes the name of the 
textfile. Under it there are three buttons to control the database. "Scan 
dir" reads a selectable directory into this database. "View" displays the 
currently active text file. The most complex button is "Search". It can 
be used to search through the all files in the database for a string. If 
you click on it, a window opens, which asks you for an string to search 
for. Then it asks for a record to start the search. If you simply hit 
enter, it will begin at the first record. Then you are asked, whether you 
want to search all records or only the marked ones. After that Fiasco 
asks you, whether you want to write the results to a file. Then the last 
option comes, "Interactive searching". If you activate this, you will be 
asked for every found string, if you want to display the file at this 
place. After that the searching starts. If you want to break the 
searching, simply hit Ctrl-C. 

    The database contains the data for the FAQ (Frequently Asked 
Question) files on the Meeting Pearls II CD-ROM. If you don`t own the CD 
ROM, use Record/Delete all Records to get rid of the data. 
@endnode 


@node ALLPATTERNS "All Searchpatterns" 

@{b}@{u}All Searchpatterns@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}
    Pattern	Supported field types	function
@{ub}
--no pattern--   all types            exact matching.

    #?      @{"String" link FT_Str}, @{"Extern" link FT_Ext}, @{"Datatypes" link FT_DT}   An unknown string with undefined length.
                                        
    ?       @{"String" link FT_Str}, @{"Extern" link FT_Ext}, @{"Datatypes" link FT_DT}   An unknown character.

    > x     @{"Integer" link FT_Int}, @{"Slider" link FT_Sld}             A number, which is greater than x.

    < x     @{"Integer" link FT_Int}, @{"Slider" link FT_Sld}             A number, which is less than x.

    >= x    @{"Integer" link FT_Int}, @{"Slider" link FT_Sld}             A number, which is greater or equal x.

    <= x    @{"Integer" link FT_Int}, @{"Slider" link FT_Sld}             A number, which is less or equal x.

    !=      @{"Integer" link FT_int}, @{"Slider" link FT_Sld}             A number, which is not equal x.




 

    Detailed descriptions are available with the @{"field documentations" link FieldTypes}. 

@endnode 
@node RELCHECKLIST "Relation Checklist" 

@{b}@{u}Relation Checklist@{ub}@{uu}


@{b}·@{ub}  create key field "there". Optionally activate "unique key". 

@{b}·@{ub}  create real field "there". In case of string, extern or datatypes, 
   remember "max chars". 

@{b}·@{ub}  save project. 

@{b}·@{ub}  create key field "here". Must be the same type as "there". 

@{b}·@{ub}  create real field "here". Must be the same type as "there". In the 
   case of string, extern or datatypes, "max chars" must be equal. 

@{b}·@{ub}  save project. 

@{b}·@{ub}  open relation requester for real field "here". 

@{b}·@{ub}  select key "here" 

@{b}·@{ub}  select relation file 

@{b}·@{ub}  select key and real field "there". If the correct field is not 
   displayed, check type and in case of string, extern or datatypes max 
   chars. 

@{b}·@{ub}  select Ok 

@endnode 
@node CLIPBOARD "Implementation of the Clipboard support" 

@{b}@{u}Implementation of the Clipboard support@{ub}@{uu}

The menuitems @{"Cut Record" link MnCutRecord}, @{"Copy Record" link MnCopyRecord} and @{"Paste Record" link MnPasteRecord} use the clipboard 
to store data temporarily. The clipboard of the Amiga OS is meant to 
provide a interface for different programs to share certain types of 
data. To make this possible, the clipboard may only contain IFF data. 

    Fiasco uses unit 0 of the clipboard and stores its data in IFF-FTXT 
files with a specific format. Each field gets a separate chunk. In this 
chunk the field content is stored in ASCII format. 

    The order of the chunks depends on the internal field list of Fiasco. 
Fiasco also uses this order to find out, which data belongs to which 
field while pasting the clipboard-contents. 

    With most other programs, you cannot create such structured IFF-FTXT 
files. The pasting in other programs is better supported. For example the 
conclip- program pastes the data correctly, while MultiView displays only 
the first chunk. 
@endnode 


